    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>In mediocriter, imperfecteq[ue] excellentibus, Minuit pra[e]sentia famam: vt nuper in Sordello, et Piccinino:
                    (pra[e]sertim cum magna Virtus non cerneretur, sed parua persona): In perfect&egrave; autem, potenterq[ue] Excellentibus,
                   </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Sordello"/>
                    <person name="Nicholas Piccininus"/>
                    <emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Superat</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>pra[e]sentia Famam:</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Vt olim in Salomone, et</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Solomon"/>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Scipione; cu[m] a peregrinis,</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Scipio Africanus"/>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>honoris erg&ocirc;</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>inuiserent[u]r</marginalia_text> 
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>In excellent things, presence lessens reputation moderately and incompletely: 
                as recently in Sordello and Nicholas Piccininus (especially when a great virtue is not distinguished, but an unimportant person [is]). 
            But in excellent things, presence surpasses reputation completely and powerfully: as once  in Salomon and in Scipio. Since therefore, they are watched over by 
            strangers of honour.</translation> 
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Strategems,</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>practicable in the assault, &amp;</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>defence of Cittyes, Townes, Castles,
                    forts, [etc]. Notable matter: for Conquerours, Aduenturers, Experimenters of fortunes by Sea, &amp; Lande,
                    Pirates, [etc] aspiring to new principalityes, or particular bootyes, or hostile reuengments [etc].</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Suddain, &amp; incredible surprizes, with sufficient power, may do much, &amp; peraduenture work woonders.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Virtutis Ducis, Comes fortuna.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Fortune, a friend of a leader's virtue.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="90">
                    <marginalia_text>In proprijs homines Symphatijs, et Antipathijs facil&egrave; capiuntur.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Men are easily captured in their own sympathies and antipathies.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="270">
                    <marginalia_text>Amoris vi&acirc; semper procedendu[m] alacriter: summa Audatia, et Industria. Solus</marginalia_text>
                </position>
                <position place="tail" book_orientation="270">
                    <marginalia_text>fo[e]liciss[imi]s Cursus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>On the path of love, one must always proceed briskly: with the greatest boldness and diligence.
            The only course for the greatest happiness.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
